80 89\n1) C Paper Mfg pfd I 10 1\nDi*\u00bbt Nall Sec Pfd I 68 75\nEm\u00bb*r Bromo-Selu. \u201dA\u201d 31 i 33\nFederal Storage Pfd 11\u201d 130\nFed.-Am Co Com 29 L 1 31\nFed.-Am. c o pfd I 98S 101\n\u2022La ns ton Monotype 104 ll\u201d s\u2019i\nMer Tr a- sure Com 1\u201d7 114\nMer Tr A- Stge pfd 94\u2019* 9'.\nNatl Mtge A- In\\ Pfd I 5 6\nM*rgv\u00bbnthaler Lino 89\nPeoples Drug S pfd 9$ 11 1\nIleal Est M A- G i\u2018<d 6\u2019 j 7\nSecurity Storage 1\u201d9 112\nTor Ref A- Wit Corp 45 50\nThe \u2022\u2019a rpel Corp 2 \u00a37\nW\u2019 Xech Mtge Com 81*\nWash Med Bide C0rp...... i 1..,..\nW'lwd I.olhri.p Pfd W 1112\n\u2022Ex. dividend.\nBROKERS FEAR\nNEW REACTION\nWarnings of the possibility of a\nfurther reaction in the market\nwere broadcast in financial circles\ntoday.\nMarket may be subject to some\npressure over the week-end.\u2014\nHORNBLOWER WEEKS.\nThe action of the market sug\ngests caution.\u2014E. F. HUTTON\nCO.\nWould not add to longer pull\ncommitments at this time. \u2014OTIS\nCO.\nContinue to favor purchase of\nselected stocks on reactions.\nTOBEY KIRK.\nBelieve majority of stocks can\nbe replaced at more attractive\nlevels before many weeks are past.\n\u2014EMANUEL CO.\nA recovery near the recent\nhighs is possible, but we are not\nimpressed with the prospects.\u2014\nJOHN MUIR CO.\nDECLARE EXTRA DIVIDEND\nDirectors of McKeesport Tin\nplate Company have declared an\nextra dividend of 50 cents a share\non the common stock in addition\nto the regular quarterly dividend\nof $1 a share, both dividends being\npayable January 2, 1931, to stock\nholders of record December 15,\n1930.\nof $157,910 in October, 1929. Ten\nmonths ended October 31, net\ndeficit was $1,671,942.37, com\npared with a net deficit of sl,-\n544,185.92 in corresponding 1929\nperiod.\nST. LOUIS SOUTHWESTERN\n\u2014Net income for October was\n$83,476 against $423,668 in Octo\nber, 1929. For ten months ended\nOctober 31. deficit, after charges,\n$115,390, compared with a net\nprofit of $1,172,813 in correspond\ning 1929 period.\nSATURDAY-NOVEMBER 29\u20141930\n-Pre. l\u00bb10- Nam* aad N\u00ab*\nHigh Low Dividend Rata High Low Cloaa Ck'xa\n38H 30 Swift Intern (2H) 32 31M 32 4- Ji\nT\nS6Ji 7JI Technicolor 11 11 11\n7Ji Teck Hugh O (60 s*l 5*4 s*/i\n19Ji 8J\u00ab Tex Oil AL 12 12 12 H\nSJI 2 Thatcher Sec 2J4 2k 2k\n10k 554 Tranaco Air T.... 55i SJI 5k J\n9 2k Tri Cont war 2k 2k 2k\n22k 3k Tublze Chat 8... 6k 6 6'4\n28k 6- Tung S L (2) 7k 7k 7M+\nU\n36! X 13 Jngerleider Finan 24 24 24\n16k 4 Unit Carr Fa <.\u00ab0) 4k 4k 4k\n30k 6k Unit Corp war... 8k \u00abk 8k\n8k 2k United Dry Dita.. 3 3 3'+ h\n44 V Unit Fnd C0r.... 9k \u00bbk 9k\n28k 7Jt United Gas new.. 9 8k 9\nIlk 3k Urilt Gas new war 3k '.Ji 3k\n99k 86k United Gas of (7). 8k 86k b I'4\n56 24 Unit LA F A (1) 6k .\u20196'4 26 i- k\n119 k 95 Uni LAP cv pf .8k 98k 98k- k\n8 1 US A int Sec.... I\u20194 Ik |J4+ k\n75 34 US A int S Ipf (5) 42k 4.\u2019k 42k- k\n22k 5k U S Electric 6k 6'4 6k k\n26k 5 U S Foil B (1).... 4k 4k 4k- k\n20k 6k U 8 Lines pfd (1) I 6\u20194 7\nok 2k U S Rub R A (1!4). 2 2 2 k\n16?\u00bb 6k Unit Ver Ex (2).. 7k 7JI 7k\n3k Ik Utah Apex Mi (k) Ik Ik I'4\u201c k\n2b 8k Util PA L n (1).. 11 10k 11 k\nV\nJ7k 59k Vacuum Oil (4i... 64k 63k 3k\u2014 k\nW\n61 22 Walgreen C 0.... 21k Xk 21k\u2014 k\n13k 5k Walker H (1) tk 6k 6k\nk k Wenden Cop\u2019r.... k !'t\u2014 k\n46J1 18, t West Air E (.60). 13 19 19\nZ\n21k 3 Zonlte Prod (D... 10 9k 10 k\nDividend aymbnia: a, and extra; b. etock; a, or >4%\nes common.\n\u2022Ex dividend. tEi rlcht.\nROCKEFELLER IS\nOPTIMISTIC\nJohn D. Rockefeller, 'jr., on his\nreturn from Europe, spoke opti\nmistically on economic conditions\nthroughout the world and ex\npressed his faith in the ability\nof the people to solve their pres\nent problems.\nAsked to comment on the pres\nent business depression and the\nprosepcts of a turn for the bet\nter, Mr. Rockefeller declared:\n\u201cI have no message except\nthat I am very hopeful as al\nways. There are many prob\nlems, grave and difficult ones,\na.nd no one knows just how\nthey will be solved, but they\nwill be solved ultimately. That\nI believe.\u201d\nHe concluded by saying:\n\u201cWe as a nation have never\nhad more to be thankful for\nthan we have today. That is\nmy own personal feeling.\u201d\nShopping for Christina* in 11 plranure\nwhen ynu iimp the convenient \u201cChristmas\nGift Suggestion*\" published in today's\nClassified Ads.\nAims Purposes Policies\nThe Better Business Bureau is a voluntary organization of\nbusiness men formed to promote accuracy and fair play\nbetween business and the consumer.\nIts aim is to build public confidence in legitimate business\nand to break down, public patronage of fraudulent business.\nIt is the foe of unfair advertising and unethical and im\nproper selling methods in all lines of business.\nIt makes its work effective by answering inquiries and\nendeavoring to adjust complaints from the public. Last\nmonth alone, the number of these came to one thousand,\nthree hundred and twenty.\nIts decisions are unbiased. It grinds nobody\u2019s axe. Its\nservices are given without pay.\nThe appearance of this\nannouncement in these\ncolumns is evidence that\nthis newspaper supports\nand cooperates with the\nBetter Business Bureau\nfor your protection.\nThe Better Business Bureau\nof Washington, D. C.\n337 Evening Star, Building\nNational 8164\nBond Market Weakness\nBars Stocks Rise\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nDirector of New York Univereity\nBureau of Business Research\nand Former Economist of\nFederal Trade Commission\nToday and tomorrow I will dis\ncuss the bond market and its\nrelation to the general situation.\nIt is widely believed\u2014and cor\nrectly, I think\u2014that bonds are a\ngood barometer of the broader\nstock market movements. This is\ntrue because bond prices are very\nsensitive to money rates and\nbonds are bought for investment.\nThe bond market reflects finan\ncial conditions and investment\ndemand.\nAfter 1926 it seemed that the\nbond market barometer was no\nlonger working. But with the\npassing of the \u201cnew era\u201d the old\nrules may be working again.\nWhat are they?\nPast Performances\nAlways in the past bond prices\nhave fallen before a major de\ncline in stock prices, usually lead\ning by from 5 to 16 months.\nUsually, too, bonds rise at the\nend of a bear market. A sus\ntained recovery in bonds usually\nleads a bull movement in stocks.\nOnce a bear market is well\nestablished, following a sustained\ndecline in bonds, it will continue\nuntil the decline in bonds is\ndefinitely checked.\nAn upturn in bonds, however,\ndoes not always mark the end\nof a bear market in stocks. For\nexample, in 1920 there was a\nfalse in bonds which came\na year ahead of the final bottom\nin stocks. And bonds rallied in\nthe early part of 1930, only to\nreact from March op to date.\nThis is one reason why I have\nnot been very enthusiastic about\nthe stock market. The bond\nmarket does not give a good\naccount of itself. If, at a time\nwhen money rates are much be\nlow the yield on bonds, investors\nwon\u2019t buy bonds, something must\nbe the matter with investment\ndemand.\nConditions Uncertain\nWhy don\u2019t bonds do better?\nThere are a good many reasons,\nbut first I would put uncertainty.\nInternational conditions are un\ncertain. The business outlook is\nuncertain. What is to be done\nabout readjusting the gold hold\nings of the United States and\nFrance? What do the large se\ncurity loans of our banks mean?\nSecond, I would point out that\non average bonds are not especial\nly cheap. Except for the peak in\nearly 1928, bonds last March were\nthe highest since 1912. According\nto one average, bonds are now\n84.4. But in the low month of\n1917 they were 74\u2014in 1921, 68\u2014\nin 1923, 77. This is particularly\ntrue of such Government and\nmunicipal bonds as the banks buy.\nBuyers\u2019 Position\nThird, there is the position of\nlarge institutional buyers\u2014banks,\ninsurance companies, etc. Not only\ndo they seem to want only short\nterm. high-priced issues, but they\nare limited by large collateral\nloans and loans on policies.\nFourth, American investors are\nstill \u201cstock conscious.\" The aver\nage man has not gotten back to\nbonds yet.\nFifth, down through June new\nbond issues were quite heavy, and\nit seems probable that undigested\nbonds still press down on the\nmarket. The sad case of the Ger\nman s\u2019is may be mentioned.\nI think the bond market ba\nrometer is working again, but that\nit has not yet signalled a bull mar\nket in stocks.\nSTOCKS HALLY\nON DULL DAY\nBy W. S. COUSINS\nNEW YORK. Nov. 29 (1.N.5.).\nStocks rallied at the week-end in\none of the dullest Saturday ses\nsions since the midsummer. In\nstead of attempting to widen the\nprice declines in the leading\nstocks, professionals were gener\nally on the buying side, paying\nslightly higher prices for the\nleading automobile, department\nstore, copper, steel and utility\nshares. The rails and oils were\nstill under pressure, though sharp\nrecoveries were made by some\nof the high-priced rails. Atchi\nson. after opening at 183 Vi for a\nloss of 3 points, spurted to 188\nnear the close.\nCopper stocks moved up in the\nfinal period on announcement\nthat no red metal was available\nunder 11 cents a pound. Kenne\ncott closed about 2 points higher,\nat 28Vi. American Smelting up\n1% at 51 7 a, and Anaconda Cop\nper up 1% at 36\u2019/z.\nUnited States Steel and Amer\nican Can led the final rally for\nthe industrials, the former gain\ning a net advance of IV< at\n145 r i, while Can closed IV2\npoints higher, at 116V4- West\ninghouse gained IV4 at 99 5/ s.\nThe Dow Jones averages\nshowed a gain of 2V4 points for\nthe industrials and half a point\nfor the rails. Stock sales totaled\n694,500 shares, exclusive of in\nactives and odd-lots, the lowest\nturnover since August 23.\nComplete 160 Mile\nSinclair Pipe Line\nThe new Sinclair pipe line\nfrom Oklahoma City pool to\nserve the company\u2019s Coffeyville\nrefinery was completed today. It\nwill be tested at once and im\nmediately thereafter put in op\neration. The line, which con\nsists of approximately 160 miles\nof 12-inch and 16 miles of 8-inch\npipe, was built by the Sinclair-\nTexas Pipe Line Company, a 100\nper cent subsidiary of Sinclair\nConsolidated Oil Corporation.\n17","height":"30255","width":"24255"}}
